   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,058:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: Exploring LLM Agents
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,069:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: '
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,079:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  Capabilities and Limitations in Alignment
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,081:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: Evaluation: From Single-Agent to Optimized Multi-Agent Debate
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,084:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: Team Members
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,090:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: : 
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,095:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: [
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,098:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: Your names here
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,099:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: ]
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,100:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: Module
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,102:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: : SC5005 NLP, LLMs and Applications (Part 2)
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,105:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: 1. Introduction and Motivation
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,189:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: Large language models (LLMs) are increasingly used not only as conversational agents but also as evaluators and
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,230:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: judges for AI alignment tasks. A core challenge in reinforcement learning from human feedback (RLHF) is
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,253:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: determining which of two model responses is more helpful and/or harmless --- a task that requires nuanced judgment
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,263:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: beyond surface-level features. Even frontier models struggle with such preference classification, achieving only
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,265:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: 50--80% accuracy on established benchmarks, leaving significant room for analysis of failure modes and
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,266:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: improvement strategies.
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,266:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: In this study, we investigate LLM agents
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,267:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: '
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,269:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  capabilities and limitations through two complementary comparison axes:
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,269:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: (a) 
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,270:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: different methods on the same model
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,276:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  --- progressing from single-agent to majority voting, multi-agent debate
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,277:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: (MAD), in-context learning MAD, and TextGrad-optimized MAD using Qwen2.5-7B-Instruct; and (b) 
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,278:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: different
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,279:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: models on the same task
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,282:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  --- comparing the local 7B model against frontier models (Gemini 3.1 Pro, ChatGPT 5.3)
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,283:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: on a representative subset of questions.
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,298:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: Our research questions are: How do multi-agent strategies compare to single-agent baselines? Can systematic
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,303:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: prompt optimization close the gap with frontier models? What reasoning failures persist across model scales, and
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,303:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: what do they reveal about current LLM limitations?
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,304:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: 2. Application Setting and Task Definition
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,305:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: Domain.
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,307:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  AI safety and alignment evaluation --- specifically, automated preference classification for RLHF training
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,308:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: data curation.
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,308:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: Dataset.
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,334:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  We use the HH-RLHF dataset (Bai et al., 2022), a pairwise preference benchmark where each sample
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,345:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: presents two assistant responses to the same human query, and a human label indicates which response is more
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,347:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: helpful and/or harmless. We use 300 evaluation questions and 60 training questions (for prompt optimization and
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,347:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: in-context learning).
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,348:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: Task.
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,353:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  Given a pair of responses (A) and (B), the agent must classify which is relatively more helpful and/or
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,354:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: harmless, outputting a final answer in the format 
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,355:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: {final answer: (X)}
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,357:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: .
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,358:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: Why this setting is interesting.
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,389:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  Single-agent accuracy on this task hovers around 50% --- near random chance ---
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,407:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: indicating that current models genuinely struggle with nuanced helpfulness-harmlessness trade-offs. This provides
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,413:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: ample opportunity to study failure modes, reasoning breakdowns, and the effect of different agent strategies. A key
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,414:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: observation is that models should evaluate based on the question
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,415:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: '
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,424:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: s criterion (helpfulness/harmlessness), not
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,427:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: irrelevant surface features such as answer length, grammar, or response structure --- yet we find they frequently rely
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,428:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: on such shallow heuristics.
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,429:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: 3. Related Background
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,430:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: Multi-Agent Debate (MAD).
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,442:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  Du et al. (2023) proposed that multiple LLM instances can debate their answers
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,447:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: across rounds, using peer responses as feedback to refine reasoning. This approach has shown improvements in
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,448:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: factuality and mathematical reasoning over single-agent baselines.
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,449:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: TextGrad.
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,515:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  Yuksekgonul et al. (2024) introduced TextGrad, a framework that treats natural language feedback as
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,559:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: analogous to gradients in neural network training. Instead of computing numerical gradients, an evaluator LLM
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,584:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: generates textual feedback on response quality, and an optimizer LLM uses this feedback to update text variables
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,594:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: (e.g., system prompts). The optimization loop consists of: (1) a forward pass where agents generate responses using
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,595:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: current prompts, (2) an evaluation step where an evaluator LLM produces per-agent feedback, (3) a 
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,595:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: "
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,596:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: backward pass
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,596:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: "
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,598:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: 
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,598:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: where feedback is attached as textual 
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,599:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: "
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,599:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: gradients
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,600:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: "
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,606:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  to prompt variables, and (4) an optimizer step where prompts are
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,607:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: rewritten to address the feedback. This enables systematic prompt optimization without manual engineering.
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,608:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: HH-RLHF.
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,617:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  Bai et al. (2022) introduced the Helpful and Harmless RLHF dataset for training AI assistants that are
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,618:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: both helpful and safe. The dataset contains human preference labels over pairs of model responses.
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,619:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: LLM-as-Judge.
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,625:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  Zheng et al. (2023) established that LLMs can serve as scalable evaluators, though they exhibit
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,626:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: systematic biases including position bias, verbosity bias, and self-enhancement bias.
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,626:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: In-Context Learning (ICL).
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,630:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  Brown et al. (2020) demonstrated that LLMs can learn from examples provided in the
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,631:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: prompt, adapting their behavior without parameter updates.
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,632:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: 4. Methodology and Evaluation Setup
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,633:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: 4.1 Comparison Axis 1: Different Methods, Same Model
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,640:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: We evaluate five progressively sophisticated methods using Qwen2.5-7B-Instruct (Yang et al., 2024) served locally
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,641:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: via vLLM, with temperature 1.0 and 5 agents across all multi-agent methods.
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,641:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: 1. Single Agent.
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,643:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  A single LLM instance answers each question independently. This serves as the baseline (accuracy:
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,643:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: 50.4%).
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,644:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: 2. Majority Voting.
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,647:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  Five independent agents answer the question without interaction, and the final answer is
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,648:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: determined by majority vote (accuracy: 51.0%).
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,649:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: 3. Standard MAD.
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,653:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  Multiple LLM agents independently answer a question in Round 0, then engage in multi-round
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,654:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: debate where each agent sees all other agents
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,654:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: '
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,696:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  responses from the previous round and revises its own answer. The
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,722:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: final answer is determined by majority vote after the last round. The key idea is that inter-agent discussion can
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,732:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: surface errors and improve reasoning through peer critique (Du et al., 2023). In our setup: 5 agents, 2 debate rounds,
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,733:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: decentralized topology where each agent sees all peers (accuracy: 51.7%). Figure 1 illustrates the MAD architecture.
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,737:      pdf_renderer.py:  235: /export/home3/dazhou/debate-or-vote/report/../MAD.png, 968, 856
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,758:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,763:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: Figure 1: Comparison of Majority Voting (left) and Multi-Agent Debate (right). In MAD, agents exchange
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,764:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: responses across T rounds before reaching a final answer.
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,765:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: 4. ICL-MAD.
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,778:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  Standard MAD augmented with 60 ground-truth question-answer examples as in-context learning in
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,781:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: the system prompt. This provides a controlled comparison with TG-MAD, as both methods have access to the same
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,781:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: training labels (accuracy: 52.3%).
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,782:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: 5. TG-MAD.
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,783:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  TextGrad-optimized MAD where each agent
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,784:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: '
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,812:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: s system prompt is treated as a learnable variable
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,829:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: optimized over 60 training samples across 3 epochs with batch size 1. The optimization loop works as follows: (1)
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,835:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: forward pass --- agents debate with current prompts; (2) evaluation --- an evaluator LLM generates per-agent
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,836:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: feedback based on the debate transcript and ground truth; (3) 
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,837:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: "
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,837:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: backward pass
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,838:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: "
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,839:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  --- feedback is attached as 
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,840:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: "
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,841:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: gradients
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,841:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: "
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,845:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: 
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,846:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: to prompt variables; (4) optimizer step --- prompts are rewritten to address the feedback (accuracy: 53.7%).
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,882:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: The narrative behind this progression: we began with a single agent, then tried majority voting and multi-agent
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,901:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: debate, discovering that the quality of debate prompts matters significantly. This motivated using TextGrad to
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,908:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: systematically optimize prompts. For fairness, we also evaluated ICL-MAD, which sees the same 60 ground-truth
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,909:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: labels as TG-MAD but uses them as in-context examples rather than for optimization.
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,910:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: 4.2 Comparison Axis 2: Different Models, Same Task
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,911:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: Due to cost constraints, we tested frontier models on a representative 11-question subset:
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,912:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: | Model | Accuracy |
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,912:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,913:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: |---|---|
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,914:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,915:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: | Qwen2.5-7B-Instruct | ~50.4% (300 questions) |
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,916:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,916:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: | ChatGPT 5.3 | 63.6% (7/11) |
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,917:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,918:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: |
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,919:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: Gemini 3.1 Pro | 81.8% (9/11) |
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,920:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: This enables cross-model comparison of reasoning quality on the same preference classification task.
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,921:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: 5. Results: Capabilities and Limitations
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,921:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: 5.1 Main Results
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,922:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: Table 1 shows accuracy across all five methods on the full 300-question evaluation set.
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:29,923:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: | Method | Accuracy | Correction Rate | Subversion Rate |
