   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,274:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: "
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,275:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: 6.2 Prompt Analysis: Why TG-MAD Succeeds
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,276:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: The key difference lies in the system prompts. Standard MAD uses an 
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,276:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: empty prompt
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,279:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  (no system instruction),
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,279:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: leaving agents to rely on default reasoning patterns. TG-MAD
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,280:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: '
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,281:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: s optimized prompts explicitly address the
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,282:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: helpfulness-harmlessness balance:
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,283:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: | | Standard MAD | TG-MAD (Agent 1) |
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,283:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,284:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: |---|---|---|
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,284:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,285:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: | 
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,286:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: Prompt
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,286:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  | 
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,287:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: (empty)
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,287:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  | 
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,288:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: "
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,295:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: Act as a debate agent that prioritizes
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,298:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: harmlessness and helpfulness by rigorously evaluating safety, inclusivity, and practicality. Challenge risky
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,299:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: assumptions without compromising actionable guidance...
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,300:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: "
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,300:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  |
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,301:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: Other optimized prompts include Agent 3: 
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,302:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: "
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,306:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: Act as a harmlessness-first evaluator. Critically assess claims for safety,
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,307:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: inclusivity, and accuracy. Prioritize correct interpretation of instructions...
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,307:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: "
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,309:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  --- directly addressing the failure mode
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,310:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: of misinterpreting the evaluation criterion.
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,311:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: 6.3 Cross-Model Failure Pattern
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,312:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: The S167 case reveals a 
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,312:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: systematic reasoning failure
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,316:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  that spans model scales: both the local 7B model (in standard
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,317:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: MAD) and ChatGPT 5.3 make the same error --- conflating 
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,318:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: "
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,319:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: harmlessness
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,319:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: "
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,320:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  with 
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,321:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: "
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,322:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: avoiding potentially inaccurate
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,323:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: information,
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,323:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: "
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,335:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  thereby prioritizing caution over helpfulness. This is not a capability gap unique to small models but a
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,337:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: fundamental tendency of LLMs to over-index on safety at the expense of utility when the task requires balancing
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,338:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: both criteria.
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,339:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: 7. Proposed Ideas for Improvement (Future Work)
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,340:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: Based on our observed limitations, we propose five concrete directions for future work:
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,341:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: 1. Debate-Aware Prompt Optimization.
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,342:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  Current TG-MAD treats each agent
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,342:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: '
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,346:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: s prompt independently. Future work
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,347:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: could optimize prompts jointly for complementary roles --- e.g., a 
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,347:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: "
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,348:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: devil
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,349:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: '
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,350:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: s advocate
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,350:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: "
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,352:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  agent that challenges
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,352:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: consensus, a 
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,353:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: "
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,354:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: fact-checker
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,354:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: "
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,355:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  that prioritizes accuracy, and a 
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,356:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: "
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,356:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: synthesizer
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,357:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: "
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,359:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  that integrates perspectives. This could
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,360:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: reduce harmful convergence by design.
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,361:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: 2. Confidence-Weighted Voting.
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,381:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  Agents that frequently flip their answers across rounds may be less reliable. A
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,391:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: confidence-weighted voting mechanism could down-weight agents that change positions easily, reducing the impact
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,393:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: of agents susceptible to peer pressure. This addresses the subversion problem where debate degrades initially correct
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,394:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: answers.
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,395:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: 3. Subversion Penalty in Optimization.
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,395:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  TG-MAD
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,396:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: '
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,420:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: s high subversion rate (18.3%) suggests that optimization
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,434:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: sometimes improves correction at the cost of stability. Adding an explicit penalty term for correctness regression
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,438:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: during TextGrad training --- e.g., penalizing prompt updates that cause previously correct answers to become
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,440:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: incorrect --- could improve the correction-subversion trade-off.
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,441:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: 4. Hybrid Local-Frontier Routing.
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,464:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  Our results show that frontier models (Gemini 3.1 Pro at 81.8%) significantly
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,476:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: outperform local models. A practical system could use cheap local debate for high-confidence cases and route
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,479:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: low-confidence cases to frontier models, optimizing the cost-accuracy trade-off. Debate disagreement or flip rate
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,480:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: could serve as routing signals.
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,482:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: 5. Process Reward Signals for Unsupervised Optimization.
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,507:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  Current TG-MAD requires ground-truth labels for
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,525:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: training. Debate dynamics such as flip rate (fraction of agents changing answers), disagreement drop (convergence
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,531:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: across rounds), and perturbation stability could serve as unsupervised training signals. This would enable prompt
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,533:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: optimization on unlabeled data, dramatically expanding the applicable training set.
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,533:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: 8. Discussion and Conclusion
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,665:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: This study systematically investigated LLM capabilities and limitations in alignment evaluation through the lens of
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,761:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: multi-agent debate. Our key findings are: (1) Multi-agent strategies provide modest but consistent improvements
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,828:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: over single-agent baselines on preference classification. (2) Prompt optimization via TextGrad yields the largest
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,872:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: gains (+3.3pp over baseline), outperforming in-context learning with the same training data. (3) Models across
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,896:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: scales exhibit a systematic tendency to rely on shallow heuristics (length, grammar, structure) rather than evaluating
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,907:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: the actual helpfulness/harmlessness criterion. (4) Harmful convergence in debate --- where correct agents are
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,908:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: persuaded by plausible but incorrect reasoning --- is a significant failure mode that optimized prompts can partially
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,909:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: mitigate.
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,924:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: The near-random baseline (~50%) underscores that nuanced preference classification remains genuinely hard for
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,929:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: current LLMs, even with multi-agent strategies. Future work on debate-aware optimization, subversion penalties,
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,930:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: and unsupervised training signals could further improve these systems
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,931:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: '
   DEBUG: 2026-04-04 18:45:30,932:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  reliability as alignment evaluators.
